HEPATITIS A - NEW ZEALAND: BACKGROUND
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Fri 7 Apr 2006
From: Dr. Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: The Gideon Database online, Fri 7 Apr 2006 [edited]
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>

Year / Cases reported
---------------------
1984 / 539 [approximate rate 16 per 100 000]
1985 / 380
1986 / 251
1987 / 158
1988 / 176
1989 / 134
1990 / 150
1991 / 224
1992 / 289
1993 / 257
1994 / 179
1995 / 338
1996 / 311
1997 / 347
1998 / 145
1999 / 119
2000 / 107
2001 / 61
2002 / 106
2003 / 70
2004 / 49
2005 / 49 [approximate rate 1 per 100 000]
Notes
-----
1. 1998 - Included 6 outbreaks (31 patients).
2. 1999 - Included 5 outbreaks (34 patients).
3. 2000 - Included 17 requiring hospitalization.
Seroprevalence surveys
----------------------
27.9 percent of adults in Christchurch
Notable outbreaks
-----------------
1999 - An outbreak (14 cases) was reported in the Auckland immigrant community.
2002 - An outbreak (81 cases) in Auckland was caused by contaminated
blueberries.
2005 to 2006 - An outbreak (21 cases) in Christchurch was associated with a
child care center.
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
[ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Steven Berger for extracting these background data
from the Gideon Database. The proportion of travel-related cases in each
year is not stated. - Mod.CP]
